    "name": "Humerus",
    "type": "Long Bone",
    "region": "Arm",
    "overview": "The humerus is the long bone of the arm. It extends from the shoulder to the elbow and forms the skeleton of the arm.",
    "features": "Head, anatomical neck, surgical neck, greater tubercle, lesser tubercle, intertubercular sulcus, deltoid tuberosity, radial groove, capitulum, trochlea, medial and lateral epicondyles.",
    "attachments": "Deltoid, pectoralis major, latissimus dorsi, teres major, supraspinatus, infraspinatus, subscapularis, brachialis, coracobrachialis, triceps brachii and others.",
    "bloodSupply": "Primarily supplied by the nutrient artery and branches of the anterior and posterior circumflex humeral arteries.",
    "nerveSupply": "The bone itself receives innervation from the periosteal nerves. Clinically related nerves include the axillary, radial, median and ulnar nerves.",
    "ossification": "Primary ossification begins during fetal life. Secondary ossification centers appear in the head, greater tubercle, lesser tubercle and distal end before eventually fusing.",
    "clinical": "Common injuries include fractures of the surgical neck, shaft fractures involving the radial nerve, and supracondylar fractures."
